s-q1aR7cI_K1TOzghZVqDQNSiohb9Jkwa8cwFoaXs9EzPJDrNe-317S8ZKlBVxA1jc0Y3Otk1frkjdD9-iX4qLQPPWib1bKeI7ADuDsF4KkSWtcDeboWvV3zRmoteIET7S6BjGI0WfJ_JvRZ6MJeHhK4YKTyvt8XWYi8B4jtHK9IBmMv61DvflXy6L1tmsVg4ASg1HEhDAPQwZOilHkT8ZEJlr8dPPzN3zPKMuCQbryg3bQnBcoAYbvgyeFImYI6xggzB1i6-_F1XbmDdsKi9kITTjNY3UHpthUXHlgryHYso6DSEQXdNvGRNHPX93txUmgamv3wSwFatIgdrt1RMbnPYLYSHrInW2Bw30qfnf8x17sE7gbe2dO_lF55C6AYLtHNKr-veCVuExy5JUsWxtHQ1mkxJ6U9BScrysqofGw9HfWCSUkIcD1oWDk9um5MZYPq1Tm2PbfKBwgMdn0EHuyAg==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating server implementation options**\\n\\nI'm considering using ServerSocket instead of the jdk.httpserver module to keep things minimal. Implementing an HTTP server with ServerSocket could be easier with multithreading while ensuring predictability. It seems Native image might need --add-modules for jdk.httpserver, which I'd like to avoid. If I go with TcpHttpServer, I should be cautious about connection handling, especially for DELETE requests. I could also think about adding a timeout for the accept loop for robustness. It might just make more sense to use ServerSocket from java.base for a smoother experience.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Designing a simple Selenium server**\\n\\nI'm working on creating a `FakeSeleniumServer` that implements `AutoCloseable`. It uses a `ServerSocket` and a single-threaded executor for handling requests. I'm considering how to manage connections, making sure it can handle multiple at once, perhaps sequentially. The `acceptLoop` accepts incoming sockets and processes them. I'll be using `BufferedReader` to read headers efficiently while ensuring I handle the request body correctly without blocking. Finally, the response will be formatted properly with the appropriate headers for JSON, using UTF-8 encoding for the body.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Implementing session handling**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out how to use an `OutputStream` for handling requests. In the `handle` method, I'll extract the HTTP method and path from the incoming request. If the request is a POST to `/session`, I need to set up the body string, count down, and respond with JSON for a new session. If it's a DELETE request for `/session/test-session`, the response should be `{\\\"value\\\": null}`. I’m also thinking about whether I should include a GET request for `/status` before creating a new session.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_4xfsHLQcSOeY7V4e9TZMQWb6|fc_00b0b265a43ee47b0169fd5cde5cc081a0b0afe080ed6d6b07", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.fluentlenium/fluentlenium-core/6.0.0/src/test/java/io_fluentlenium/fluentlenium_core/DefaultWebDriverFactoriesInnerRemoteWebDriverFactoryTest.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage io_fluentlenium.fluentlenium_core;\n\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\n\nimport io.fluentlenium.configuration.DefaultWebDriverFactories;\nimport io.fluentlenium.configuration.ProgrammaticConfiguration;\nimport java.io.BufferedReader;\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io.InputStreamReader;\nimport java.io.OutputStream;\nimport java.net.InetAddress;\nimport java.net.ServerSocket;\nimport java.net.Socket;\nimport java.net.SocketException;\nimport java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;\nimport java.time.Duration;\nimport java.util.Locale;\nimport java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;\nimport java.util.concurrent.Executors;\nimport java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit;\nimport java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicReference;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\nimport org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;\nimport org.openqa.selenium.remote.DesiredCapabilities;\n\npublic class DefaultWebDriverFactoriesInnerRemoteWebDriverFactoryTest {\n    @Test\n    void createsRemoteWebDriverFromConfiguredRemoteUrl() throws Exception {\n        try (FakeSeleniumServer server = FakeSeleniumServer.start()) {\n            ProgrammaticConfiguration configuration = new ProgrammaticConfiguration();\n            configuration.setRemoteUrl(server.remoteUrl());\n            DesiredCapabilities capabilities = new DesiredCapabilities();\n            capabilities.setBrowserName(\"firefox\");\n\n            DefaultWebDriverFactories.RemoteWebDriverFactory factory =\n                    new DefaultWebDriverFactories.RemoteWebDriverFactory();\n            WebDriver driver = factory.newWebDriver(capabilities, configuration);\n\n            try {\n                assertThat(driver).isNotNull();\n                assertThat(server.awaitNewSessionRequest()).contains(\"firefox\");\n            } finally {\n                driver.quit();\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    private static final class FakeSeleniumServer implements AutoCloseable {\n        private static final Duration TIMEOUT = Duration.ofSeconds(10);\n\n        private final ServerSocket serverSocket;\n        private final ExecutorService executor;\n        private final AtomicReference<String> newSessionRequest = new AtomicReference<>();\n\n        private FakeSeleniumServer(ServerSocket serverSocket) {\n            this.serverSocket = serverSocket;\n            this.executor = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor(runnable -> {\n                Thread thread = new Thread(runnable, \"fake-selenium-remote\");\n                thread.setDaemon(true);\n                return thread;\n            });\n        }\n\n        static FakeSeleniumServer start() throws IOException {\n            InetAddress loopbackAddress = InetAddress.getLoopbackAddress();\n            ServerSocket serverSocket = new ServerSocket(0, 50, loopbackAddress);\n            serverSocket.setSoTimeout((int) TIMEOUT.toMillis());\n            FakeSeleniumServer server = new FakeSeleniumServer(serverSocket);\n            server.executor.execute(server::serve);\n            return server;\n        }\n\n        String remoteUrl() {\n            return \"http://\" + serverSocket.getInetAddress().getHostAddress() + ':' + serverSocket.getLocalPort();\n        }\n\n        String awaitNewSessionRequest() throws InterruptedException {\n            long deadline = System.nanoTime() + TIMEOUT.toNanos();\n            while (System.nanoTime() < deadline) {\n                String request = newSessionRequest.get();\n                if (request != null) {\n                    return request;\n                }\n                TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS.sleep(10);\n            }\n            throw new AssertionError(\"Timed out waiting for a WebDriver new-session request\");\n        }\n\n        private void serve() {\n            while (!serverSocket.isClosed()) {\n                try (Socket socket = serverSocket.accept()) {\n                    handle(socket);\n                } catch (SocketException e) {\n                    if (!serverSocket.isClosed()) {\n                        throw new AssertionError(\"Fake Selenium server socket failed\", e);\n                    }\n                } catch (IOException e) {\n                    throw new AssertionError(\"Fake Selenium server failed\", e);\n                }\n            }\n        }\n\n        private void handle(Socket socket) throws IOException {\n            socket.setSoTimeout((int) TIMEOUT.toMillis());\n            BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(\n                    new InputStreamReader(socket.getInputStream(), StandardCharsets.UTF_8));\n            String requestLine = reader.readLine();\n            if (requestLine == null) {\n                return;\n            }\n\n            int contentLength = readContentLength(reader);\n            char[] body = new char[contentLength];\n            int offset = 0;\n            while (offset < body.length) {\n                int read = reader.read(body, offset, body.length - offset);\n                if (read < 0) {\n                    brea